API Endpoint
1.An endpoint is the specific URL of an API used to access a particular resource.
2.Each endpoint represents a specific type of data or operation.

Examples:
/users → get all users
/users/1 → get a specific user
/products → get product list

Important points:
1.One API can have multiple endpoints
2.Changing the endpoint changes the data you receive
3.Endpoints are like different “options” available in an API

Analogy:
Just like a restaurant menu has different items, an API has different endpoints

4. JSON (Data Format Used in APIs)
1.JSON stands for JavaScript Object Notation
2.It is the standard format used by APIs to send and receive data

Why JSON is used:
1.Lightweight (fast to transfer)
2.Easy to read and understand
3.Easy to use in JavaScript/Angular

JSON Structure:
1.Data is stored in key–value pairs
2.Objects are written using {}
3.Arrays are written using []

Example (Object):

{
"id": 1,
"name": "Sharmit",
"email": "test@gmail.com"
}

Example (Array):
[
{ "id": 1, "name": "A" },
{ "id": 2, "name": "B" }
]

Key Points:
1.Keys are always strings
2.Values can be string, number, boolean, array, or object
3.Angular uses this JSON data to display content in UI


